BfZGpWV5MU8pVaOyrCzmIrbsY5DznxgQ93l/Pmf0ym6tDVagLMpTx%2b3wSp4h54ZJIHl9jIUJ4KuFmuxJRqifq8QTEkNnMPQHZmQYkTEKND3UQXJjN0joMUweIzR4hQRr0MzQxCR%2b7IM5CjVOqYGKIYHiEx52eAUqEPRwZEUW8%2bTRQcbVEHQTF0Z2ZPtJwMLIKBvIGiQBm%2baEF2XLSzwrS50ZiH3WUwXI%2bvQblC0Kiviuz3xCO5RkP1Gdy3qzly6/cqQC0lfePmUahtZEID%2bLkzQV9UskANBy5HgcO5EDMjvibIaQJBcS62V8IWvHVt/ro3D2q4RoJXRHd2xnMBhIfcl1Xd/zbdtWFEWSJBau55qmKSuyJEu6oXueZ1mWpmlAdV33/Qw5g0qSgeeC0HM9FrIss%2b9NhgJYll0HSp7resPhEFqe4wX8uZ6mar1eD2T4Ok4mRl/qm5bpTgZMeSzbYu24GbSjdF50F4irC78LIUe/34cNi8yWYShNBux55TAgVDKMrJEKggCVeB2NRrxGUaQqqj7StVF2veI4Ro5MYjf7%2bQC7QienDBR9kElQBoo%2bIAjkDKpk2kJBvKIbrwIZ/2SmRHnX%2b7uQ3VKpqsgVerI4jJPJELJmIfT3ELIix/ngfMfvpMK7tyg5zvsfffDps08TNynvl7GZqqq1Wq3ZbB4dHeH0er3earU6nU6pVCL8bquPKtxiffm2fL8oFcfRGNdjfuKBMCO0WBONWF0kBjFui2nhVvwoFh8%2beu%2bzyiexHh9WD7vdbqPRwPZYHT%2b02%2b1bFPr8%2bAvqURqI590tDAAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==' /%3e%3c/svg%3e\" width=\"600\" alt=\"Average Total Transfer Size Over a Request Chart\" data-srcset=\"/assets/static/Average-Total-Transfer-Size-Over-a-Request-Chart.bd6740a.6884d79e9c6d4f10dae8102f1a321706.png 600w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" data-src=\"/assets/static/Average-Total-Transfer-Size-Over-a-Request-Chart.bd6740a.6884d79e9c6d4f10dae8102f1a321706.png\"><noscript><img class=\"g-image g-image--lazy g-image--loaded\" src=\"/assets/static/Average-Total-Transfer-Size-Over-a-Request-Chart.bd6740a.6884d79e9c6d4f10dae8102f1a321706.png\" width=\"600\" alt=\"Average Total Transfer Size Over a Request Chart\"></noscript></p>\n<p>According to <a href=\"http://w3techs.com/technologies/history_overview/programming_language\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">w3techs.com</a>, 16.7% of all sites on the internet use ASP.NET as of 1st August 2015, lets assume half of those (8.35%) will use ASP.NET Core in a few years time. So, we can say that very roughly 21498 Terabytes of the worlds bandwidth is consumed on ASP.NET HTML requests per year.</p>\n<p>If the average wasted bandwidth is six bytes out of a total of 57 KB per HTML request, then we come to a grand total of around 2.3 Terabytes of bandwidth saved per year. I must admit, that's a lot of bandwidth but I still thought it would be a lot more than that.</p>\n<h1 id=\"html-minification\"><a href=\"#html-minification\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" version=\"1.1\" width=\"22\" height=\"22\" aria-hidden=\"aria-hidden\"><path fill=\"currentColor\" fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>HTML Minification</h1>\n<p>An even better solution would be to minify the HTML. There are solutions like <a href=\"http://webmarkupmin.codeplex.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Web Markup Min</a> for ASP.NET Core but it works at runtime and is a little involved to set up, so all but the most determined developers use this feature.</p>\n<p>Then there is <a href=\"http://www.deanhume.com/Home/BlogPost/a-simple-html-minifier-for-asp-net/2097\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Dean Hume's</a> compile time minifier which sounded perfect. In Dean's post he gets savings of around 20-30% by minifying his HTML. If we applied a conservative 20% saving to all ASP.NET Core HTML requests, that would work out to be a 4300 Terabyte saving in global bandwidth per year!</p>\n<p>So far, I've only mentioned the bandwidth saving but downloading smaller HTML files will also mean quicker page load times. HTML is the first thing a browser downloads before it can go off and download all the other CSS, JavaScript, fonts and images a site needs to display a page. Making this download smaller, is a small but effective way to get pages up quicker.</p>\n<p>These days, MVC has things like CSS and JavaScript minification built in as standard. To squeeze out even more performance, HTML minification is the next logical step.</p>\n<p>So I made <a href=\"https://github.com/aspnet/Razor/issues/423\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">this</a> suggestion for ASP.NET Core to implement Dean's compile time minification of Razor views by default. So far, it's not been taken up but I live in hope and write this blog post to show how cool a feature it is.</p>\n<p>Please do go and post your support for this feature. We don't necessarily need to use Dean's technique, minifying HTML could just as easily be a Grunt or Gulp task.</p>\n<h1 id=\"conclusions\"><a href=\"#conclusions\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" version=\"1.1\" width=\"22\" height=\"22\" aria-hidden=\"aria-hidden\"><path fill=\"currentColor\" fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Conclusions</h1>\n<p>This post contains huge leaps of guess work and estimation. I hope my maths is up to scratch but I would not be surprised if I was off by a decimal point or two. Still, we are talking huge numbers here and I hope I've convinced you that minifying HTML is worth the effort.</p>\n"}}]}}},"context":{}}